Exploratory Data Analysis: Analyzing California Wildfires from 2000-2023¶

Data Source: California Open Data Portal¶

https://gis.data.cnra.ca.gov/maps/CALFIRE-Forestry::california-fire-perimeters-all-1¶

The purpose of this notebook is to explore methods of exploratory data analysis utilizing popular data analysis libraries such as pandas, matplotlib, and seaborn. The main questions we'd like to explore in this dataset are:¶
  • What have been the general trend for California wildfires over the last 23 years? Overall, do wildfires in California seem to be getting better or worse over time?
  • What kind of extreme outlier events have occured in the past 23 years?
  • What are the main causes of wildfires? Have these changed over time?

#a better, automated option 

# Convert Month to string 
fires['Month'] = fires['Month'].astype('string')

#create a dictionary of the month numbers and words
month_words_dict = {
    '1.0': 'January',
    '2.0': 'February',
    '3.0': 'March',
    '4.0': 'April',
    '5.0': 'May',
    '6.0': 'June',
    '7.0': 'July',
    '8.0': 'August',
    '9.0': 'September',
    '10.0': 'October',
    '11.0': 'November',
    '12.0': 'December'
}

# Replace numeric month values with their names
fires['Month'] = fires['Month'].replace(month_words_dict)

# set up data and create polynomial for trendline
x = yearly_counts['Year']
y = yearly_counts['Total_Incidents']

z = np.polyfit(x, y, 1)  # Linear fit (degree 1)
p = np.poly1d(z)

# Generate x values for the trend line
x_fit = np.linspace(x.min(), x.max(), 100)
y_fit = p(x_fit)

# Plot the trend line
plt.plot(x_fit, y_fit, color='red', linestyle='--', label='Trend Line')

plt.show()

Miscellaneous is a large category in all years, but the metadata doesn't provide any information as to what qualifies as miscellaneous. So, let's cut that out as well and see what the data looks like.¶
In [51]:
common_causes_all_years = fires[(fires['Cause'] != 'Miscellaneous') & (fires['Cause'] != 'Unknown/Unidentified')]

cause_counts = common_causes_all_years.groupby(['Year', 'Cause']).size().reset_index(name='Count')
cause_counts

#find the top 5 causes for each year
top_causes_per_year_clean = (cause_counts.sort_values(by=['Year', 'Count'], ascending=[True, False]).groupby('Year').head(5))
top_causes_per_year_clean

pivot_cleaned = top_causes_per_year_clean.pivot(index='Year', columns='Cause', values='Count').fillna(0)
pivot_cleaned
